  <title>dèidh</title>
  <p><strong>dèidh</strong> is a noun which nowadays only appears in the compound preposition <strong>an dèidh</strong> <en>after</en> 
    (alternatively <strong>às dèidh</strong>). In certain dialects, <strong>dèidh</strong> is pronounced and spelled <strong>deaghaidh</strong>.</p>
  <p>Like all compound prepositions, <strong>an dèidh</strong> has a full range of conjugated forms – <strong>nam dhèidh</strong> <en>after me</en>, <strong>nad dhèidh</strong> <en>after you</en>, etc. <boxlink ref="#forms"/> </p>
  
  <box id="forms">
    <title>Conjugated forms of <mark>an dèidh</mark></title>
    <p>The conjugated forms of <strong>an dèidh</strong> are –</p>
    <ul>
      <li>first singular – <mark>nam dhèidh</mark> <en>after me</en></li>
      <li>second singular – <mark>nad dhèidh</mark> <en>after you</en></li>
      <li>third singular feminine – <mark>na dèidh</mark> <en>after her/it</en></li>
      <li>third singular masculine – <mark>na dhèidh</mark> <en>after him/it</en></li>
